As Nord Stream 1 is shut down for (long scheduled) maintenance, I'm expecting now following scenerio: The Russians will announce that, well there are some issues with Nord Stream 1 and it won't be possible to take it back into operation anytime soon. But conviently Nord Stream 2 is basically operational and all it needs is just the last rubberstamp of approval and the gas can flow like nothing has ever happened. To be honest I would be surpriced if the Russians are not trying this move. The question is now: How react the Germans? Gas is usually thought as energy source but I don't see the main problem there. I'm expecting that Germany is just firing up it's coal plants (probably using lignite, dirtiest energy source of all) in shortterm and in midterm even taking back the remaining nuclear plants into service. But the main concern is in my estimate the demand for gas in various industries to produce petrochemicals, pharmaceuticals, nitrogen fertilizers just to name a very few from a very long list for which natural gas is essential. And this is one of the economical strongholds in Germany and most important above all: jobs. And jobs in Germany are the killer argument against everything. In my estimate it depends now how quickly the German government is able to tap into other sources for natural gas. At the moment Nord Stream 2 seems to me not so dead like many think or want to believe. At the moment I give it a 23% going operational this year. Please let me know where you agree and where you think I got it wrong.

I don't think we will see Nord Stream 2 going online. Period. Four months ago, when I made my last forecast on that question the chance of actually Nord Stream 2 pumping gas to Germany by the end of this year was still a possibility and I'm sure the Russians tried hard to persuade the Germans to start it's operation. But now the political decision has been made in favour get off Russian energy and taking a more supportive stance towards Ukraine by sending more lethal and heavy weaponry. Germany has been criticised for it's reluctance (And rightfully criticised, in my opinion) but to Germany's defence: It's not a easy turn arround for Germans after 70 years of a more peaceful and by times pacifist policy in Europe and especially towards Russia so energy and trade policy has been one aspect of it and as we know today Putin sees something like this as weakness happy to exploit it for his ( or in his view for Russia's) advantage. It's a long and hard earned and still fragile trust from countries like Poland and France. So being more assertive towarts Russia is for many contemporary Germans unsettling, but the shift in German energy and foreign policy is clear. Nord Stream 2 is dead.
